The paper deals with geometric data structures and algorithms for fat rectangles, which is a topic within computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses range reporting and rectangle stabbing, which are classic problems in data structures, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) another likely sub-category. The use of space and time complexity analysis suggests cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) as a possible sub-category. The paper also mentions the size of the universe, which is a concept commonly used in database systems, making cs.DB (Databases) another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of data structures for efficient querying, which is a topic within artificial intelligence, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) a less likely but still possible sub-category.
